ce:section.ce:para:
As shown in Fig. 4
                        a, visible light harvesting capability of the FN-CQDs/g-C3N4 followed the order of FN-CQDs/g-C3N4(50) > FN-CQDs/g-C3N4(40) > FN-CQDs/g-C3N4(30) > pure g-C3N4. The optical absorption of FN-CQDs/g-C3N4 exhibited a red-shift ranging from visible to NIR light as the FN-CQDs did not exhibit partial oxidation and g-C3N4 loading was able to alter the optical properties. It was reported that partial oxidation in FN-CQDs occurred upon oxidation of precursors with a high surface hydroxyl group [29]. The visible light harvesting capabilities improved upon the introduction of FN-CQDs into g-C3N4 because FN-CQDs had intrinsic optical absorbance that enhanced photocatalytic performance under sunlight. Among FN-CQDs/g-C3N4 composites, FN-CQDs/g-C3N4(50) demonstrated excellent absorption capability as shoulder absorption was observed after 700 nm. This phenomenon was associated with the formation of localized states in the band gap and led to improved visible light absorption [46]. When the concentration of FN-CQDs increased, the band gap (Eg
                        ) of the composites reduced, leading to higher exploitation of visible light. The band gap of all photocatalysts was calculated using the Tauc plot with Kubelka-Munck function F(R). The observed band gap energy of bare g-C3N4 was 2.97 eV. Upon the addition of FN-CQDs onto the bare g-C3N4, the band gap had decreased. The band gap reduction was due to the presence of a sub-band energy level between bare g-C3N4, and FN-CQDs [47]. The sub-band energy level formation was mainly caused by the π-electron delocalization phenomenon in the FN-CQDs/g-C3N4 conjugated system [48]. The narrow band gap of the FN-CQDs/g-C3N4 composites allowed the increased utilization of solar irradiation which promoted the generation of photogenerated charge carriers for photocatalytic activities [49].
